{"title":"LLM in a Flash: Efficient Large Language Model Inference with Limited Memory","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"On-device LLM inference is constrained when model parameters exceed available DRAM; naively reloading large weights from flash each token is dominated by flash bandwidth/latency, making it too slow.","method":"Store full model weights on flash and keep only embeddings and attention weights resident in DRAM to minimize repeated transfers. Exploit FFN activation sparsity by training a small low-rank predictor that, using only the current layer’s attention outputs, anticipates which intermediate neurons will be active after ReLU; then load only the corresponding FFN up/down weights from flash. This selective persistence and predictor-guided loading substantially reduces flash→DRAM traffic with marginal impact on zero-shot accuracy. (Evidence: selective persistence and sparsity use: lines 74–79, 76–77, predictor design and training: line 80, accuracy impact: lines 88–97.)"},{"problem":"Even with selective loading, small scattered reads and reloading across tokens cause high latency; efficient reuse and low-overhead management of loaded weights in tight DRAM are needed.","method":"Introduce a Sliding Window cache that retains weights for neurons predicted active over the last k tokens, loading only the incremental difference for each new token and freeing out-of-window neurons as the window slides. Pair this with a preallocated per-layer data structure (concatenated up/down matrices, pointer mapping, bias, num_used, last_k_active) that supports O(c·d_model) deletions and append-only inserts without DRAM reallocation. This reduces both per-token I/O and DRAM management overhead as generation proceeds. (Evidence: sliding window definition and s_agg behavior: lines 100–105, 102–104; DRAM data structure and operations: lines 124–136.)"},{"problem":"Flash storage has poor throughput for small, random reads, bottlenecking sparsity-driven selective loading.","method":"Increase effective sequentiality and chunk size via row–column bundling: for each neuron, co-locate the up-projection column and the corresponding down-projection row on disk so each predicted-active neuron is fetched as a contiguous 2·d_model·num_bytes block, improving read throughput. Combine with multi-threaded I/O (32 threads) to exploit storage parallelism. Ablations show sparse-read throughput rising from ~1.25 to ~2.25 GiB/s and I/O latency halving (e.g., 164→87 ms) when bundling is enabled. (Evidence: bundling mechanism and doubled chunk size: lines 108–110; parallelized reads: line 169; Table 2 improvements: lines 154–160.)"}]}
